dern fascism were copied by several subsequent productions, making Titus the most characteristic, as well as the most influential, contemporary performance of the play.Friedman’s work extends Alan Dessen’s original study to include Taymor’s film, along with chapters devoted to the efforts of international directors including Gregory Doran, Silviu Purcarete, and Yukio Ninagawa. This expanded volume will prove essential to students of Shakespeare’s play, along with scholars interested in the tragedy’s gruesome yet occasionally comical performance history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aBill Alexander.  aDaniel Mesguich.  aDeborah Warner.  aEdward Ravenscroft.  aGale Edwards.  aGregory Doran.  aIrving Wardle.  aJeannette Lambermont.  aJulie Taymor.  aLucy Bailey.  aMichael Maggio.  aPeter Brook.  aPeter Stein.  aRciahrd Rose.  aShakespeare.  aSilviu Purcarete.  aStanley Wells.  aTitus Andronicus.  aTrevor Nunn.  aYukio Ninagaw.1 aDessen, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610191440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526101914423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526101914/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles